Intependent T Test Example 1 Alarafi & Song (2024) conducted a reent study comparing online distance learning and traditional in-person education at King Saud University in Saudi Arabia, with a focus on understanding how different educational modalities affect student achievement. By analyzing the final test scores of freshman students in five core courses over the 2020 (in-person) and 2021 (online) academic years, the research provides empirical insights into the efficacy of online versus traditional education.

RQ: Does learning modality differentially impact achievement?

Model Learning Modality (Online v. InPerson) –> Achievement

Statistical Mode Achievement = Modality + Error

SET UP

#read in the data
dat_ach <- read.csv("independent ttest demo.ach.csv")
colnames(dat_ach) <- tolower(colnames(dat_ach))
# The "Modality" variable was entered as a character so we need to convert it to a factor
dat_ach$modality <- as.factor(dat_ach$modality)

DESCRIPTIVES

# Get descriptive statistics for the entire sample
desc_ach <- descriptives(dat_ach, vars = c('modality', 'ach'), hist = TRUE, freq = TRUE, sd = TRUE, se = TRUE, skew = TRUE, kurt = TRUE)

T TEST

#vars = outcome variable
jmv::ttestIS(data = dat_ach, vars = 'ach', group = 'modality', effectSize = TRUE, ci = TRUE, meanDiff = TRUE, desc = TRUE)
## 
##  INDEPENDENT SAMPLES T-TEST
## 
##  Independent Samples T-Test                                                                                                                             
##  ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────── 
##                          Statistic     df          p             Mean difference    SE difference    Lower       Upper                    Effect Size   
##  ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────── 
##    ach    Student's t    16.67146 ᵃ    5189.000    < .0000001           3.958222        0.2374250    3.492769    4.423675    Cohen's d      0.4629404   
##  ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────── 
##    Note. Hₐ μ <sub>InPerson</sub> ≠ μ <sub>Online</sub>
##    ᵃ Levene's test is significant (p < .05), suggesting a violation of the assumption of equal variances
## 
## 
##  Group Descriptives                                                           
##  ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────── 
##           Group       N       Mean        Median      SD          SE          
##  ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────── 
##    ach    InPerson    2663    39.48499    39.44000    8.068814    0.1563594   
##           Online      2528    35.52677    35.38000    9.029543    0.1795880   
##  ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

APA WRITE UP An independent t-test confirmed that students who took their Freshman year courses in-person (M = 39.49) had significantly higher levels of achievement than those in the online cohort (M = 35.53), t(5189) = 16.67, p < .001, d = 0.46, 95% CI [3.49,4.42]. Learning modality had a moderate effect on achievement, the mean performance scores for in-person students were just under a half a standard deviation above those of online students.

Independent T Test Example 2 Music performance anxiety has been known to impact musicians abilities to perform and find success in their industry. Martin-Gagnon and Creech (2019) sought to determine if the setting in which a jazz musician was playing, solo or in an ensemble, made a difference in the anxiety they experienced prior to performing.They collected data from 76 performers who played primarily solo or primarily in ensembles, and collected data regarding their music performance anxiety.

RQ: Does the setting a musician plays music in predict anxiety before performing?

Model: Setting (solo, ensemble) –> music performance anxiety Stats model anxiety = setting + error

SET UP

#read in the data
dat_jazz <- read.csv("independent ttest demo.jazz.csv")

# The "Group" variable was entered as an integer so we need to convert it to a factor
dat_jazz$setting <- as.factor(dat_jazz$setting)

DESCRIPTIVES

# Get descriptive statistics for the entire sample
desc_jazz <- descriptives(dat_jazz, vars = c('anxiety'), hist = TRUE, sd = TRUE, se = TRUE, skew = TRUE, kurt = TRUE)

APA WRITE UP An independent t-test confirmed that musicians who play solo (M = 111.15) do not have significantly different anxiety than those who play in ensembles (M = 117.92), t(74) = 1.07, p = .288, d = 0.25, 95% CI[-5.822,19.36]. There was a small effect, with the mean anxiety of ensemble musicians only .25 of a standard deviation above solo musicians.

Intependent T Test Example 3 Leadership qualities were explored in 362 college seniors who were surveyed regarding several variables, including their leader self-efficacy (confidence in leader abilities). You, the researcher, are wondering if taking the Intro to Leadership course, which over half of the students in the sample were enrolled in, has any impact on their leader self-efficacy.

RQ: Does taking the Intro to Leadership class predict higher Leader Self-Efficacy scores at the end of college?

Model Class Enrollment –> Leader Self-Efficacy

Statistical Mode Leader Self-Efficacy = Class Enrollment + Error

SET UP

#read in the data
dat_lead <- read.csv("independent ttest demo.lead.csv")

# The "Group" variable was entered as an integer so we need to convert it to a factor
dat_lead$Class <- as.factor(dat_lead$Class)

DESCRIPTIVES

# Get descriptive statistics for the entire sample
desc_lead <- descriptives(dat_lead, vars = c('Class', 'LeaderSE'), hist = TRUE, freq = TRUE, sd = TRUE, se = TRUE, skew = TRUE, kurt = TRUE)

T TEST

#vars = outcome variable
jmv::ttestIS(data = dat_lead, vars = 'LeaderSE', group = 'Class', effectSize = TRUE, ci = TRUE, meanDiff = TRUE, desc = TRUE)
## 
##  INDEPENDENT SAMPLES T-TEST
## 
##  Independent Samples T-Test                                                                                                                                 
##  ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────── 
##                               Statistic    df          p             Mean difference    SE difference    Lower       Upper                    Effect Size   
##  ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────── 
##    LeaderSE    Student's t     37.38286    360.0000    < .0000001           4.612000        0.1233721    4.369380    4.854620    Cohen's d       4.305908   
##  ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────── 
##    Note. Hₐ μ <sub>intro</sub> ≠ μ <sub>none</sub>
##

##  Group Descriptives

##                Group    N      Mean        Median      SD          SE           
##  ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────── 
##    LeaderSE    intro    255    75.06000    75.06411    1.050000    0.06575355   
##                none     107    70.44800    70.54574    1.120000     0.1082745   
##  ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

APA WRITE UP An independent t-test confirmed that students who took the Intro to Leadership class (M = 75.06) had significantly higher leader self-efficacy than students who did not (M = 70.45), t(360) = 37.38, p < .001, d = 4.31, 95% CI [4.37,4.85]. There was a large effect of taking the intro class, the mean self-efficacy of the students in the class was over 4 standard deviations higher than that of those who did not.
